\section{PROBLEM 1}
1.Find the slope of a line, which passes through the origin, and the mid-point of the
line segment joining the points P = $\myvec{ 0\\-4}$  and B =$ \myvec{ 8\\0}$
\\ SOLUTION:\\
\\Given,
$\vec{P}$ = $\myvec{ 0\\-4}$ ; $\vec{Q}$ = $ \myvec{ 8\\0}$ \\
\\The mid-point is given by,\\
\\$\vec{Q}$= $\frac {P+B} {2}$ = $\frac {1} {2} \vec{P}$  + $\frac{1}{2} \vec{B}$ = $\frac {1} {2} \myvec{ 0\\-4}$  + $\frac{1}{2} \myvec{ 8\\0}$ \\
\\Therefore, $\vec{Q}$ =$\myvec{ 4\\-2}$ \\
\\The slope of the line is given by,\\
\\ m =  $\vec{Q}$ -  $\vec{0}$ = $\myvec{ 0\\-4}$ + $\myvec{ 0\\0}$ = $\myvec{ 4\\-2}$ \\

\section{PROBLEM 2}
2. Without using distance formula, show that points $\vec{A}$ = $\myvec{ -2\\-1}$,\ $\vec{B}$ = $\myvec{ 4\\0}$ ,\ $\vec{C}$ = $\myvec{ 3\\3}$ and \ $\vec{D}$ = $\myvec{ -3\\2}$ \
are the vertices of a parallelogram.\\
\\SOLUTION:\\
\\Given,
\begin{align}
\vec{A} &= \myvec{ -2\\-1}\ \vec{B} = \myvec{ 4\\0}\ \vec{C} = \vec{ 3\\3} \ \vec{D} =\myvec{-3\\2} \\
\end{align}

\\To show that the given points are the vertices of a parallelogram:\\
\begin{enumerate}
\item $\vec{A}-\vec{B} = \vec{D}-\vec{C} $
\item  $\vec{A}-\vec{D} = \vec{B}-\vec{C} $
 \end{enumerate}
%\\ $\vec{A}-\vec{B} = \vec{D}-\vec{C} $  $\vec{A}-\vec{D} = \vec{B}-\vec{C} $\\
So,
\\$\vec{A}-\vec{B}$ = $\myvec{-2\\-1}$ - $\myvec{4\\0}$ = $\myvec{-6\\-1}$\\
\\$\vec{D}-\vec{C}$ = $\myvec{-3\\2}$ - $\myvec{3\\3}$ = $\myvec{-6\\-1}$\\
\\$\vec{A}-\vec{D}$ = $\myvec{-2\\-1}$ - $\myvec{-3\\2}$ = $\myvec{1\\-3}$\\
\\$\vec{B}-\vec{C}$ = $\myvec{4\\0}$ - $\myvec{ 3\\3}$ = $\myvec{1\\-3}$\\
\\Therefore, we can now say that the given points are the vertices of a parallelogram since both the sides of the quadrilateral are parallel to each other.
